  <static seed="1333" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/divideRationalExpressions50.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{r^{5}}{r^{2}-3r}} \div {\frac{1}{r^{2}-r-6}} =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>r^{4}\mathopen{}\left(r+2\right), r\ne 0\hbox{ and }r\ne 3\hbox{ and }r\ne -2</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{r^{5}}{r^{2}-3r}} \div {\frac{1}{r^{2}-r-6}} 
      \amp = {\frac{r^{5}}{r^{2}-3r}} \cdot {\frac{r^{2}-r-6}{1}} \\
      \amp = \frac{{r^{5}}}{{r\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}} \cdot \frac{{\left(r-3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+2\right)}}{{1}} \\
      \amp = {r^{4}\mathopen{}\left(r+2\right), r\ne 0\hbox{ and }r\ne 3\hbox{ and }r\ne -2}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>r</m> and <m>r - 3</m> were canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>r \ne {0, 3}</m>.</p>
</solution>
